\begin{abstract}
  Decision-making in data markets typically features multi-agent strategic interaction, cross-stage feedback, and tightly coupled causal structure, making it a natural and demanding testbed for evaluating the decision competence of large language models (LLMs). Recent work has begun to study LLM behavior in privacy-related data-sharing decisions from game-theoretic and economic perspectives. However, most existing evaluations remain outcome-centric—focusing on metrics such as sharing rates, platform profit, or social welfare—which makes it difficult to distinguish whether seemingly reasonable behavior arises from genuine understanding of the underlying economic mechanisms, or instead from linguistic heuristics, pattern matching to training data, or prompt-induced compliance.

We propose a \textbf{mechanism-oriented benchmark for privacy externalities} to systematically assess LLMs’ mechanism understanding and inference capabilities. The benchmark instantiates three distinct economic environments, each grounded in a computable externality mechanism, and provides a reproducible theoretical solver for each scenario to generate verifiable ground truth. LLMs are embedded as strategic agents within the induced games via a multi-agent natural-language interaction protocol, and are evaluated with a unified diagnostic metric suite that jointly measures terminal outcome deviation, strategic-structure consistency with the theoretical equilibrium , and dynamic properties such as convergence and path dependence.

We evaluate 12 frontier LLMs from three model families—GPT, DeepSeek, and Qwen—including GPT-5.2, GPT-5.1, deepseek-v3.2, deepseek-v3.1, qwen-plus, and qwen3-max. Furthermore, for selected models that initially perform poorly, we introduce multi-round fictitious play to test whether mechanism feedback can substantially improve convergence and agreement with the theoretical equilibrium. Overall, our benchmark explicitly separates “outcome correctness” from “mechanism correctness,” providing a solver-backed, diagnostic evaluation tool for characterizing and comparing LLMs’ mechanism understanding, robustness, and dynamic convergence in privacy-externality data markets.
\end{abstract}

